    "blog-post.html": """<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="description" content="How to build resilient distributed workflows with CloudFlow">
    <meta property="og:title" content="Building Resilient Workflows">
    <title>Building Resilient Distributed Workflows | CloudFlow Blog</title>
</head>
<body>
    <article>
        <h1>Building Resilient Distributed Workflows</h1>
        <p class="meta">By Sarah Chen | Published October 3, 2025 | 8 min read</p>

        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>In modern cloud architectures, workflow resilience is not optional. When
        your pipeline processes millions of events per day, even rare failures compound
        into significant data loss. This post explores patterns for building workflows
        that survive node failures, network partitions, and downstream outages.</p>

        <h2>Pattern 1: Idempotent Steps</h2>
        <p>Every step in your workflow should be safe to retry. This means designing
        handlers that produce the same result regardless of how many times they execute.
        Use deterministic IDs, upsert operations, and content-addressable storage.</p>

        <h2>Pattern 2: Circuit Breakers</h2>
        <p>When a downstream service fails, don't keep hammering it. Implement circuit
        breakers that trip after N consecutive failures and automatically reset after
        a cooldown period. CloudFlow supports this natively with the RetryPolicy mixin.</p>

        <h2>Pattern 3: Dead Letter Queues</h2>
        <p>Tasks that fail after all retries should land in a dead letter queue for
        manual inspection rather than being silently dropped. CloudFlow's dashboard
        provides a dedicated view for reviewing and resubmitting dead-lettered tasks.</p>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Resilient workflows require intentional design at every layer. Start with
        idempotent handlers, add circuit breakers for external dependencies, and use
        dead letter queues as your safety net. CloudFlow makes these patterns easy
        to implement with built-in runtime support.</p>
    </article>
    <nav>
        <a href="/blog">All Posts</a>
        <a href="/blog/workflow-patterns">Related: Workflow Patterns</a>
        <a href="https://github.com/cloudflow/examples">GitHub Examples</a>
        <a href="https://broken-cdn.invalid/images/diagram.png">Diagram (broken)</a>
    </nav>
</body>
</html>""",

    "docs-api.html": """<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="description" content="CloudFlow REST API reference documentation">
    <title>API Reference | CloudFlow Documentation</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>CloudFlow API Reference</h1>
    <p>Complete documentation for the CloudFlow REST API. All endpoints require
    authentication via Bearer token.</p>

    <h2>Authentication</h2>
    <p>Include your API key in the Authorization header:</p>
    <code>Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY</code>

    <h2>Workflows</h2>
    <h3>POST /api/workflows</h3>
    <p>Create a new workflow execution. The request body must include the workflow
    definition ID and input parameters.</p>

    <h3>GET /api/workflows/:id</h3>
    <p>Retrieve the status and results of a workflow execution. Returns step-level
    details including timing, outputs, and error information.</p>

    <h3>DELETE /api/workflows/:id</h3>
    <p>Cancel a running workflow. All in-progress steps will be terminated and
    resources released.</p>

    <h2>Steps</h2>
    <h3>GET /api/workflows/:id/steps</h3>
    <p>List all steps in a workflow execution with their current state, parameters,
    and return values.</p>

    <h2>Rate Limits</h2>
    <p>API requests are limited to 1000 per minute per API key. Exceeding this
    limit returns HTTP 429.</p>

    <nav>
        <a href="/docs">Docs Home</a>
        <a href="/docs/guide">Getting Started Guide</a>
        <a href="/docs/sdk">SDK Reference</a>
    </nav>
</body>
</html>""",

